'''Tatsumi Shrine''' (たつみじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} located in Tatsumi-Minami 3-chome, {{jalink|Ikuno Ward|Q490520}}, {{jalink|Osaka City|Q35765}}.

It enshrines {{jalink|Emperor Ōjin|Q317997}} as the principal {{jalink|kami|Q11591100}}, and also enshrines Inshiki-iri-hiko no Mikoto, {{jalink|Izanagi|Q813858|Izanagi-no-Mikoto}}, {{jalink|Ame-no-Tokotachi-no-Mikoto}}, {{jalink|Amaterasu Ōmikami|Q455602}}, {{jalink|Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|Q2564508|Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto}}, and {{jalink|Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005}}.

===History===
On April 27, {{jalink|1907|Q2048}} (Meiji 40), the Hachiman Shrine (enshrining Emperor Ōjin) that had been located within {{jalink|Tatsumi Village|Q11479954|Tatsumi Village}} of {{jalink|Nakakawachi District|Q11366394}} (formerly {{jalink|Shibukawa District|Q11561609}}) was merged with five shrines in the village (the Yokono Shrine in Ōaza Daichi, Aza Inji (a Shikinaisha, enshrining Inshiki-iri-hiko no Mikoto); the Tenjin Grove in Ōaza Ikaga, Aza Ikaga; the Amateru Kōdaijin Shrine in Ōaza Nishiashiro, Aza Yoshinouchi; the Kumano Shrine in Ōaza Yagara, Aza Miyanomae; and the Tenjin Grove in Ōaza Shijō, Aza Yamagōji) through {{jalink|shrine consolidation|Q11590700|consolidation}}, and was renamed Tatsumi Shrine after the village name.

===Shikinaisha and Yokono Shrine===
About one kilometer northeast of the current location, at Tatsumi-Nishi 3-chome 9 in Ikuno Ward, there is a “Site of Yokono Shrine.” It was formerly a small shrine on a pond called “Inji-no-miya,” but on February 18, {{jalink|1731|Q6963}} (Kyōhō 16), it was identified as the Shikinaisha Yokono Shrine and renamed accordingly, with its enshrined deity designated as Inshiki-iri-hiko no Mikoto, the second imperial prince of {{jalink|Emperor Suinin|Q314850}}. The {{jalink|Nihon Shoki|Q813935}} records that the Yokono embankment was constructed in the 13th year of Emperor Nintoku’s reign, and the shrine is believed to have served as the guardian deity of this embankment.

=== External links ===
* [https://www7b.biglobe.ne.jp/tatsumi_jinja/index.html Tatsumi Shrine] (official website)

