'''Tatsumi Shrine''' (たつみじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Tatsumi-Minami 3-chome, {{ill|lt=Ikuno Ward|Q490520|WD=Q490520|1=Ikuno-ku, Osaka}}, {{ill|lt=Osaka City|Q35765|WD=Q35765|1=Osaka}}.

It enshrines {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}} as the principal {{ill|lt=kami|Q11591100|WD=Q11591100|1=Saijin}}, and also enshrines Inshiki-iri-hiko no Mikoto, {{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|WD=Q813858|lt=Izanagi-no-Mikoto|1=Izanagi}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ame-no-Tokotachi-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|Q455602|WD=Q455602|1=Amaterasu}}, {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|Q2564508|WD=Q2564508|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Koyane}}, and {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|WD=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}.

===History===
On April 27, {{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|WD=Q2048|1=1907}} (Meiji 40), the Hachiman Shrine (enshrining Emperor Ōjin) that had been located within {{ill|lt=Tatsumi Village|Q11479954|WD=Q11479954|lt=Tatsumi Village|1=Tatsumi}} of {{ill|lt=Nakakawachi District|Q11366394|WD=Q11366394|1=Nakakawachi district}} (formerly {{ill|lt=Shibukawa District|Q11561609|WD=Q11561609|1=Shibukawa district}}) was merged with five shrines in the village (the Yokono Shrine in Ōaza Daichi, Aza Inji (a Shikinaisha, enshrining Inshiki-iri-hiko no Mikoto); the Tenjin Grove in Ōaza Ikaga, Aza Ikaga; the Amateru Kōdaijin Shrine in Ōaza Nishiashiro, Aza Yoshinouchi; the Kumano Shrine in Ōaza Yagara, Aza Miyanomae; and the Tenjin Grove in Ōaza Shijō, Aza Yamagōji) through {{ill|lt=shrine consolidation|Q11590700|WD=Q11590700|lt=consolidation|1=Shrine Consolidation Policy}}, and was renamed Tatsumi Shrine after the village name.

===Shikinaisha and Yokono Shrine===
About one kilometer northeast of the current location, at Tatsumi-Nishi 3-chome 9 in Ikuno Ward, there is a “Site of Yokono Shrine.” It was formerly a small shrine on a pond called “Inji-no-miya,” but on February 18, {{ill|lt=1731|Q6963|WD=Q6963|1=1731}} (Kyōhō 16), it was identified as the Shikinaisha Yokono Shrine and renamed accordingly, with its enshrined deity designated as Inshiki-iri-hiko no Mikoto, the second imperial prince of {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|WD=Q314850|1=Emperor Suinin}}. The {{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|WD=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}} records that the Yokono embankment was constructed in the 13th year of Emperor Nintoku’s reign, and the shrine is believed to have served as the guardian deity of this embankment.

